In every Guarany town, there are a number of caciques‚ who, if men of abi- litieS, are often promoted to the office of magis- trateS, that the Indians may not suspect the Europeans of despising their nobility. There were five caciques in the town of St. Joachim, over which I presided. Their names were Don Ignatius Paranderi, Don Miguel Yeyh, Don Marco Quirakera, Don J oseph Xavier, and Don Miguel Yazuka; which last performed the office of corregidor for many years.
